Next, it was time to select the suite of developmer tools to make the website come to life. I had used a little bit of React in a previous college course (Introduction to Software Engineering), so using the React library was a no-brainer. HTML, CSS, and Javascript (using Node.js) were a given for the front-end. In the back-end, I decided to use Express, known for being the go-to server framework for Node.js. I also decided to use Axios as a means to communicate between the front-end and the back-end. Finally, I decided to use Mailgun's API to facilitate the process of sending emails.
